# /etc/sudoers — SLICC agent approval policy
#
# This file controls which agent actions require a native human approval
# prompt (an OS dialog in CLI/Electron, or a window.confirm/prompt in the
# Chrome extension) before they run. By default EVERYTHING below is commented
# out, so no extra prompts fire — uncomment a rule to start gating an action.
#
# Every line is one of three directives. A leading `NOPASSWD` tag turns a rule
# into an explicit grant (matching actions run with no prompt):
#
#   Cmnd  <glob>        Require approval before a shell command segment that
#                       matches <glob> runs (matched against each top-level
#                       segment of the command line).
#   Read  <glob>        Require approval before reading a VFS path.
#   Write <glob>        Require approval before writing a VFS path.
#
# Globs:
#   - Command globs: `*` and `**` match any run of characters, `?` matches one.
#   - Path globs:    `*` matches within one path segment (no `/`), `**` matches
#                    across segments. A trailing `/**` also matches the dir
#                    itself (so `/workspace/.git/**` matches `/workspace/.git`).
#
# Precedence: a matching NOPASSWD grant wins (no prompt); otherwise any plain
# match requires approval; no match means the action is never gated.
#
# Self-protection (ALWAYS on, not configurable): writes to /etc/sudoers and
# anything under /etc/sudoers.d/ always require approval — a NOPASSWD rule can
# never override this. Reads of these files are allowed (visudo-style).
#
# Live reload: edits to this file (and to /etc/sudoers.d/*) take effect for the
# agent immediately, with no restart. When you choose "Always" on a prompt the
# generalized pattern is appended to /etc/sudoers.d/granted (auto-managed —
# edit /etc/sudoers here for durable rules instead).
#
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Example rules — uncomment and adapt to taste.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# Require approval before any `git push`:
# Cmnd  git push*
#
# Require approval before force-pushing, but allow ordinary pushes outright:
# Cmnd  git push --force*
# NOPASSWD Cmnd  git push origin*
#
# Require approval before deleting anything:
# Cmnd  rm *
#
# Gate reads of a secrets directory:
# Read  /shared/secrets/**
#
# Gate writes into the git internals of the workspace:
# Write /workspace/.git/**
#
# Gate writes anywhere under /mnt (mounted external storage):
# Write /mnt/**
